What is the oldest dynasty to be represented with buildings in Kathmandu's Durbar Square?

How many kingdoms have buildings present in the Durbar Square of Kathmandu?

context: The literal meaning of Durbar Square is a "place of palaces". There are three preserved Durbar Squares in Kathmandu valley and one unpreserved in <a0_0>Kirtipur<a0_0/>. The Durbar Square of Kathmandu is located in the old city and has heritage buildings representing <a4_0>four<a4_0/> kingdoms (Kantipur, Lalitpur, Bhaktapur, Kirtipur); the earliest is the <a1_0>Licchavi<a1_0/> dynasty. The complex has <a2_0>50<a2_0/> temples and is distributed in two quadrangles of the Durbar Square. The outer quadrangle has the Kasthamandap, Kumari Ghar, and Shiva-Parvati Temple; the inner quadrangle has the Hanuman Dhoka palace. The squares were severely damaged in the <a3_0>April 2015<a3_0/> Nepal earthquake.
